ethorpe, Lincolnshire, England","Billesby, England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1406–about 1428":"about 1406–about 1428","1394–Female":"1394–Deceased","1394–Male":"1394–Deceased","1405–1478":"1405–1478","1406–1440":"1406–1440","1406–1428":"1406–1428","1411–1482":"1411–1482","1400–1428":"1400–1428","1428–1470":"1428–1470","1367–1432":"1367–1432","1373–1411":"1373–1411","1440":"1440","1373":"1373","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1470":"1470","about 1406":"about 1406","about 1428":"about 1428","1478":"1478","1411":"1411","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","about 1424":"about 1424","1386":"1386","1428":"1428","1406":"1406","1405":"1405","Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England","Billesby, England":"England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Swynford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire, Kent): habitational name from Old Swinford (Worcestershire), Kingswinford (Staffordshire), Swinford (Leicestershire), Swinford in Cumnor (Berkshire), or Swinford in Hothfield (Kent), all of which are recorded <i>Swineford</i> or <i>Swyneford</i> in medieval documents. The placenames derive from Old English <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, pig’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[{"name":"Swineford","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from one of the English places that gave rise to   Swinford  .","Americanized form of German <b>Schweinfurt(h)</b>, a habitational name from a place so named (Franconia)."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Swynford was born about 1406, in Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England, her father, Sir Thomas Swynford, was 40 and her mother, Joan Crophill, was 34. She married Sir William Bilesby about 1424, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1428, in Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 24."},"et":{"about 1406–about 1428":"umbes 1406–umbes 1428","1394–Female":"1394–Surnud","1394–Male":"1394–Surnud","1405–1478":"1405–1478","1406–1440":"1406–1440","1406–1428":"1406–1428","1411–1482":"1411–1482","1400–1428":"1400–1428","1428–1470":"1428–1470","1367–1432":"1367–1432","1373–1411":"1373–1411","1440":"1440","1373":"1373","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1470":"1470","about 1406":"umbes 1406","about 1428":"umbes 1428","1478":"1478","1411":"1411","1367":"1367","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","about 1424":"umbes 1424","1386":"1386","1428":"1428","1406":"1406","1405":"1405","Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Kettlethorpe, Lincolnshire, England","Billesby, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England"